<html>
<head>
<BODY bgcolor=#ffffff>
<title>The Week -- September 16th, 1996</title>
</head>
<body>
<center><img src="/nationalreview/images/week.gif" ALT="The Week">
</center>
<p>
<HR>
<P>
<!--------------------------------------------------------------------->

16-SEPTEMBER-1996
<P>
At the last Chicago convention, under the bad Mayor Daley, the cops whacked Yippies. Now, under the good Mayor Daley, peace reigns in the party, and the convention is in a neighborhood you wouldn't dare visit at night unarmed under normal circumstances. Progress.
<P>
<hr width=50%>
<P>
The media, quick to point out an alleged ``shortage'' of women and minorities at the Republican Convention, missed a more interesting story at the Democratic Convention -- the blatant resort to quotas in the selection of delegates. Democratic National Committee rules forbid ``mandatory quotas,'' and Bill Clinton repeatedly proclaims his opposition to them. Yet the 1996 Delegate Selection Rules require all state parties to adopt ``specific goals and timetables'' ensuring that each delegation exactly matches the Democratic electorate in the state in terms of color and sex. Rigid mathematical models and formulas are spelled out, and penalties ensue for any shortfall. As the <I>Wall Street Journal</I> points out, the result is a revealing gloss on how a re-elected Clinton Administration is likely to interpret its ``opposition'' to quotas.


<P>
<hr width=50%>
<P>

Scientists say chocolate affects the same part of the brain that is turned on by smoking marijuana. Asked to comment, President Clinton said he once put chocolate in his mouth, but didn't swallow.

<P>
<hr width=50%>
<P>


John Cardinal O'Connor has disinvited Bill Clinton from the prestigious Al Smith dinner because of the President's support of partial-birth abortions. Such an unprecedented snub of a sitting President powerfully communicates the depth of the Catholic bishops' outrage. But Cardinal O'Connor diluted that message by not inviting Bob Dole either, in order to avoid charges of partisanship. Jack Kemp and Al Gore have been invited in the presidential nominees' places. The plain, if unwelcome, fact is that one party's ticket sided with the angels on this issue, and another's didn't. On partial-birth abortion, the President hasn't let squeamishness alter his course. Neither should Cardinal O'Connor.

<P>
<hr width=50%>
<P>


The results are in. Did the networks apply the same standards to the Democratic convention that they did to the Republicans? Did Dan Rather predict walkouts and boos whenever any speaker mentioned the welfare bill? Did Tom Brokaw ask if the delegates really cared about the two-parent family? Did Jim Wooten of ABC point out that the Chicago Convention was ``well staged, craftily designed for a broadcast image of moderation that's starkly at odds with the reality on the floor''? Check your scorecards.

<P>
<hr width=50%>
<P>


Twenty-eight years ago, according to David Horowitz, Tom Hayden said, ``It might be useful . . . to fire bomb police cars'' at the Chicago Convention. Now Hayden, a state senator from California, works within the party the better to fight extremist Republicans in Congress.

<P>
<hr width=50%>
<P>


Congressional Republicans have refused to touch the issue of race preferences over the last year. No longer. If the House passes the version of the Federal Aviation Authorization Act of 1996 just endorsed by the House Transportation Committee, Republicans will finally take on the issue of quotas -- by re-authorizing one of the Federal Government's more egregious set-aside programs. The act requires that every airport applying for federal funds under the Airport Improvements Program guarantee that 10 per cent of firms doing business at the airport are minority owned. This has led to absurdities such as rental-car companies being forced to buy 10 per cent of their tires from minority firms. It also is plainly unconstitutional under the Supreme Court's <I>Adarand</I> decision. But airport bills are full of pork-laden goodies for nearly everyone, so the Transportation Committee likes to see them pass on big bi-partisan votes -- even if it means winking at the worst sort of racial bean-counting. The House leadership will end the practice, if it has a sufficient quota of courage.

<P>
<hr width=50%>
<P>


After Mississippi's Gov. Kirk Fordice used an executive order to ban gay marriage in his state, ACLU-types actually had the chutzpah to complain that this constitutes government by ``fiat,'' as if fiat hasn't been the preferred liberal mode of government for decades. Referred to the Department of Motes and Timbers, Gnats and Camels.

<P>
<hr width=50%>
<P>


At a morning meeting the first day of the Democratic National Convention, officials of the centrist Democratic Leadership Council bragged of having won the battle for the mind of their party. They can indeed point to a platform that studiously avoids leftist rhetoric and a President who, post 1994 at least, has regularly filched Republican issues. These victories are only provisional, however, as long as the muscles and tendons of the Democratic Party remain so dominated by the Left. While ``New Democrats'' trooped to the podium in the convention hall, in the streets and meeting halls elsewhere around town activists celebrated the old faith -- from AFL - CIO chairman (and Democratic Socialist) John Sweeney denouncing the ``evil'' of Newt Gingrich at an afternoon ``America Needs a Raise'' rally, to the National Education Association caucusing with top Democrats at the downtown Hyatt. All that holds the party together now is the sheer will to retain power. That, and not New Democrat centrism or any other ideological concoction, is what motivates today's Democratic Party. A DNC T-shirt says it all -- ``Win in '96,'' which is what must pass for uplift in Chicago. The last time Democrats met in the Windy City, there was talk of a ``New Politics'' of moral commitment and idealism. Chicago 1996 is about the triumph of the old politics, winning at all costs.
<P>
<hr width=50%>
<P>



Mr. H. Ross Perot, who a year ago said he would rather perform brain surgery on himself than get back into presidential politics, likes to regard himself as George Washington II, and has enough money to buy either major party, is ``accepting'' nearly $30 million in federal election funds for his Reform Party. Or to put it more plainly, he's sticking it to taxpayers. If this is his idea of ``reform,'' he's overdue for that brain surgery.

<P>
<hr width=50%>
<P>


Maybe Republicans should be happy the press didn't provide more coverage of the San Diego convention. Take the abortion controversy. Reporter after reporter explained that the Republican platform calls for a ban on all abortions. The platform's actual language -- ``we support a Human Life Amendment to the Constitution and we endorse legislation to make clear that the Fourteenth Amendment's protections apply to unborn children'' -- is silent on the issue of exceptions. ``It's a statement of principle, it's not a legislative document,'' explains Mike Russell, a Christian Coalition spokesman. The constraints of space, time, and audience attention often make it hard to convey the nuances of a story; but given the vast amount of media attention to abortion, it's puzzling why this error has become a hardy perennial of reporting on the issue. News accounts of the struggle over Dole's proposed ``declaration of tolerance'' were more accurate, but still misleading. They left the impression that all ``tolerance language'' had been stripped out of the platform. In fact, the platform refers three times to legitimate differences of opinion among Republicans: in the preamble (``In one way or another, every Republican is a dissenter''), in the statement of principles (``Because Americans are a diverse and tolerant people, they have differences of opinion on many issues''), and in the opening of the section which deals with abortion and other issues of individual rights and personal safety (``We are the party of the open door,'' etc.). By ignoring the more generic statements of tolerance, they misled viewers through omission. And Howell Raines, the <I>New York Times</I>'s editorial-page editor, provided the most mischievous free advice of the convention. Colin Powell ``could be a more serious force if he set out to rally Republican voters to take back the party from its convention zealots.'' In other words, the GOP's most popular figure should declare war on the party's base in the middle of an election year. And if liberal Democrats should benefit from this fratricide, well, that's OK too.

<P>
<hr width=50%>
<P>


Executed, by lethal injection: Mrs. Judith Curren, for being overweight and tired. Dr. Jack Kevorkian does it again, yet he still has not been nominated to be the new surgeon general.


<P>
<hr width=50%>
<P>

Bob Dole, it is said, is being whipped by President Clinton on the smoking issue. But nothing so dramatizes the Republican theme of an overbearing, blundering Federal Government as Clinton's policy toward tobacco. As it happens, his latest move -- to authorize the Food and Drug Administration to regulate the sale and advertising of tobacco products -- looks like a blunder indeed, because it commits the government to a protracted court battle with the tobacco industry that the industry will almost certainly win. Tobacco products simply don't fall within the purview of the FDA: the law gives the FDA jurisdiction only over pharmaceutical drugs, and all the elaborate regulations the FDA is likely to produce will in time be declared unconstitutional. FDA chief David Kessler knows that. But he doesn't care, wanting to use the interim period to speak to the nation as the President's anti-smoking czar. When Dole last got onto the smoking issue, he made the mistake of speaking off the cuff and then getting angry with lovable girl-next-door Katie Couric. He should choose his forum more carefully and then make the common-sense case that tobacco smoking is a pleasure which does entail a health risk, but that it is a matter of individual choice for adults whether or not they smoke: it is not a matter for Federal Government grandstanding and empire-building. Dole can legitimately warn against the Naderite zealots at the FDA who want to impose tobacco prohibition.

<P>
<hr width=50%>
<P>


Drug use over the past three years rose 78 per cent among teenagers. And that's just on the White House staff.

<P>
<hr width=50%>
<P>


<I><b>NR</b></I> has suspected from the beginning that the political provisions of the Dayton Accords -- the noble blueprint for a unitary, multi-ethnic Bosnia -- might prove unattainable. Sure enough, the Bosnian elections scheduled for September 14 look to be a great disappointment, even a setback, rather than a boost toward stable democracy. There are charges of massive vote-rigging by Serbs in contested areas over which they seek to tighten their grip; in none of the rival communities is there a great predilection for democratic procedures. The deeper problem, however, is not the vote manipulation but the consolidation of partition. (``Electoral cleansing,'' <I>The Economist</I> dubs it.) The Serb and Croat populations have made clear (in U.S. Information Agency opinion polls) that they yearn for partition. For Bill Clinton, Dayton has already served its purpose of putting Bosnia on ice until our election is past. But whoever is President next year will face an unholy mess.

<P>
<hr width=50%>
<P>


The Equal Employment Opportunity Commission has ruled that Bruce Anderson, the vegetarian in California who refused to give children on his school bus coupons for free hamburgers, was wrongfully fired. Anderson cited religious reasons for not doing his job, and the EEOC apparently agreed, setting the stage for a constitutional crisis of the first magnitude. Are cows protected by the First Amendment? Do we <I>really</I> have to eat our broccoli?


<P>
<hr width=50%>
<P>

Does mere Christianity have the same standing under the law (EEOC law anyway) as vegetarianism? Ask yourself what would happen to a school-bus driver who, contrary to job instructions, passed out invitations to go to Holy Communion.
<!------------------------------------------------------------------>
<p>
<HR WIDTH=50%>
<p>
<a href="/nationalreview/welcome.html">Return to <B><I>NATIONAL REVIEW'S</I></B> homepage</a>
<BR>
</body>

